Raman spectroscopy is a most potent, direct and non-destructive technique to characterize the structural defects of the carbon-oriented nanomaterials [41]. Raman spectra of the FNCDs (
                        Fig. 7

                        ) showed a couple of peaks at 1371 cm−1 (D band) and 1603 cm−1 (G band). D band referred to the irregularity of the disordered graphitic layer of the sp3 carbon and G band referred to the vibrations of the carbon (sp2) in the graphitic carbon framework of FNCDs. The degree of graphitization of the carbon based nanomaterials were expressed by the intensity ratio of D and G band (ID/IG). In FNCDs, the ID/IG value was 0.68 which showed the presence of a moderate degree of graphitization. Finally, from the Raman spectral results, it could be concluded that FNCDs were amorphous in nature [42–44].

Thermo gravimetric analysis (TGA) was performed to determine the thermal property of the FNCDs (
                        Fig. 8

                        ). TGA analysis of FNCDs was performed in the nitrogen atmosphere. Loss in weight of FNCDs was observed from 30 to 600 °C. The Thermogram of FNCDs showed a fall in weight of about 10–20% around 100–200 °C, indicating the eradication of the moisture or the water molecules adsorbed in FNCDs. Furthermore, the constant weight loss from 300 to 600 °C was because of the degradation of the oxygen owning groups, decomposition of the carbon skeleton and the functional moieties of FNCDs [45].
